WHAT IS IN IT

Photo Labeling Policy — five status tiers with hard rules: REAL/CONFIRMED, REPRESENTATIVE, GENERATED, BRANDED-PLACEHOLDER, and QUARANTINE. Every tier spells out what alt text says, what code comments say, and what the customer page never says. No internal agency language bleeds through.

Route-by-route slot inventory — 34 named slots across every route. Ten existing slots are marked KEEP (circuit maps, interactive components, review cards). Twenty-four new or upgrade slots are marked REPLACE, all with specific stock search direction, correct alt text, and overlay treatment. Zero slots in quarantine from prior build since the problem was absence of photos, not wrong photos.

Visual quality gate — five criteria every image must pass before it touches a slot: trade accuracy, realism, composition, honest labeling, and dark-surface fit. Kills sci-fi imagery, wrong-trade shots, and generation artifacts at intake, not at QA.

Color and type refinements — five additions on top of sage-brand.md: dark overlay gradient spec for photos (not flat black, not cyan), customer-visible vs source-comment labeling split, BRANDED-PLACEHOLDER card styling, H1 size correction for inner service pages, and WebP/dimension/lazy-load requirements.

Banned imagery registry — four categories with explicit entries: sci-fi/fake electrical, wrong trade/wrong scope, fake JAG proof, and generic contractor template look. Plus a fifth category for image text overlay violations so "24/7" and "Emergency Service" never appear even as a photo caption.

Forge/Craig requirements — numbered, concrete implementation instructions: new homepage proof strip section, image slot structure on all service pages, city photo slots on all five city pages, about page second slot, mandatory HTML comments on every image, and a fallback rule so BRANDED-PLACEHOLDER holds any slot where stock sourcing runs dry.
